<h1 class="headline">Council weighs nearly $700,000 in new wish-list spending as reserves shrink toward floor</h1>
<p class="dek">Tuesday's budget workshop laid out a two-year financial picture for Cloverdale: more requests than revenue, a healthy but declining reserve, and a dozen pitches — from a new cop to a Senior Center boost to crash-rated street barriers — that the Council must now sort into "yes," "later," and "no."</p>

<div class="byline">
  <span>Filed from the Fire District EOC, 451 S. Cloverdale Blvd.</span>
  <span>Meeting: 9 a.m., May 5, 2026 · in-person only</span>
</div>

<article>

<p class="lede">If you missed the Cloverdale City Council's special budget workshop on Tuesday morning, you missed a long, candid look at the city's books for fiscal years 2026–27 and 2027–28 — and a parade of presentations from staff and community groups asking the Council to spend money the city does not, at the moment, have a plain surplus to cover. The workshop was held in person at the Fire District Emergency Operations Center and, by design, was not streamed on Zoom or YouTube. This recap pulls together what was presented, how the dollars line up, and what the Council was asked to decide.</p>

<h2>The Big Picture: Spending Outpaces Revenue</h2>

<p>The headline number from staff's General Fund overview is simple and, for residents, important: in both upcoming fiscal years, the city expects to spend more from its General Fund than it brings in. Projected revenue for FY 26–27 is about $12.7 million; projected expenses are about $14.8 million. The following year, revenue dips to roughly $11.5 million while expenses ease to about $13.1 million. The gap is bridged by drawing down the General Fund balance, which is budgeted to fall from roughly $10.4 million at the start of FY 25–26 to about $6.8 million by the end of FY 27–28.</p>

