<p>Staff was careful to put a frame around all of this: revenues are budgeted conservatively, the General Fund Reserve sits at roughly 25%, and labor agreements are not yet finalized — so the budget carries only a placeholder 1% cost-of-living adjustment that will scale up once contracts are signed. As staff put it on slide 54, every $100,000 in additional General Fund spending shaves about one percentage point off the reserve. That is the rule-of-thumb the Council was asked to keep in mind as the rest of the workshop unfolded.</p>

<h2>Police: A New Officer, More Cameras, and Mobile Crash Barriers</h2>

<p>The Cloverdale Police Department brought several items, presented as a package. The largest is a request for an <strong>11th sworn officer</strong>. Under the timeline staff laid out, recruitment would begin July 1, 2026, the academy in January 2027, and field training would wrap up by December 2027. Half a year of trainee wages — about <strong>$87,500</strong> — would hit the 26–27 budget; a full salary of <strong>$175,000</strong> would land in 27–28, plus roughly $4,000 for academy costs and $1,700 in pro-rated uniforms. Staff noted that revenue from voter-approved Measure DD could be used to support the position.</p>

<p>Two technology requests came alongside it. <strong>Peregrine</strong> (referred to in some materials as "Peregrin") is an integrated public-safety software platform that would consolidate dispatch, records, license-plate reader data, body-worn camera footage, and reports into a single searchable system, with real-time crime mapping and CJIS-compliant data sharing with neighboring agencies. It runs roughly $29,000 to $33,000 a year on a three-year contract — and, importantly, staff described it as <em>cost-neutral</em>, paid out of the $50,000 the Cloverdale School District contributes annually for the School Resource Officer.</p>

<p>The <strong>Flock Safety</strong> camera system would expand from six license-plate-reading cameras to nine, closing what the department described as gaps at certain ingress and egress points around town. The hardware add-on costs $7,800 (with a $1,550 discount), also covered out of the SRO funds. The annual subscription rises from $17,500 to $23,400. The Police Department's executive summary emphasized that the system does not use facial recognition.</p>

<div class="pullquote">
  Expanding to nine cameras will strengthen the department's ability to detect and track vehicles tied to criminal activity… while maintaining strong privacy safeguards, including no use of facial recognition technology.
  <cite>— Cloverdale PD, Flock Safety Upgrade Executive Summary</cite>
</div>

<p>Finally, the department asked for <strong>Mobile Vehicle Barriers (MVB)</strong> — a crash-rated, federally-tested, single-person-deployable system, with trailer included, that would protect the public during downtown street closures and recurring events such as Friday Night Live. The one-time cost is approximately <strong>$130,000</strong>, proposed to come from a mix of the General Fund and impact fees. Staff framed it as a response to the rising risk of vehicles being used as weapons in pedestrian-heavy events.</p>

<p>Added together, the police department's "wish list" items — the 11th officer, additional Flock cameras (the General Fund portion, listed at $5,900), the barriers, and Peregrine — total <strong>$431,400</strong> across the two years.</p>

<h2>City Clerk's Office: A Proposed Community Engagement Department</h2>

<p>City Clerk Mike Maloney's presentation argued that Cloverdale's current model — a single City Clerk position carrying governance, public information, recreation programming, records, and elections — is structurally out of balance compared with similarly sized cities, which typically staff multiple positions in the Clerk's Office. Workload has grown in records management, Public Records Act compliance, recreation programming (in the absence of a dedicated recreation position), grant administration, and emergency-preparedness coordination.</p>

<p>The proposal would consolidate overlapping public-facing functions into a new <strong>Community Engagement Department</strong>, with two staffing options on the table: <strong>Option A</strong>, one full-time benefited position at roughly <strong>$155,000</strong>, or <strong>Option B</strong>, multiple part-time/temporary positions at roughly <strong>$84,000</strong>. Staff stressed that they were asking only for general agreement on the concept on Tuesday; specifics would return after a formal classification and compensation study. A budget amendment may be needed if changes can't be folded in before June 30.</p>

<h2>Emergency Preparedness: JDS Training Continued</h2>

<p>Staff recommended continuing emergency-preparedness training through 26–27 with <strong>JDS Management Services</strong>, at a cost of <strong>$25,000</strong> from the General Fund. The training is structured rather than one-time, focusing on the Emergency Operations Center: resource requesting (field → city → county), damage assessment, disaster finance tracking for federal reimbursement, and building out a logistics section.</p>

