<h3>Senior Center: From $15,000 to $40,000</h3>
<p>Anthony Ramirez, Administrative Manager of the Cloverdale Senior Multipurpose Center, wrote to the city in April requesting a $40,000 contribution for FY 26–27, up from the $15,000 the city has historically contributed. The request breaks down to $15,000 for programs and services (healthy-aging classes, the congregate senior lunch, food distribution, a community produce market, medical-equipment lending, support groups), $10,000 for administration and operations, $10,000 for insurance (general liability, cyber, volunteer, workers' comp), and $5,000 for health and safety items.</p>

<h3>Historical Society: Saving the Gould-Shaw House Paint</h3>
<p>Cloverdale Historical Society President Kate Barrett wrote to City Manager Kevin Thompson on April 22 asking for a contribution or grant of at least $15,000. The Society's letter — which doubles as a small annual report — described a new board, a new website, a decision not to refill the Executive Director position, and resulting savings. The money is wanted for facilities work: dry-rot repairs on the historic Gould-Shaw House and the History Center, the back of which the Society described as "essentially bare of paint." Total estimated repair cost is more than $60,000, to be tackled in installments over two years.</p>

<h3>CloveReady / Cloverdale Resiliency</h3>
<p>The $20,000 resiliency program, proposed to be administered through the Chamber of Commerce, would build out response playbooks (communications, volunteer management, donations), produce a public Stay-Safe guide, expand the CloveReady, Know Your Zone, and Nixle awareness campaigns, and increase the city's presence at events such as Friday Night Live and National Night Out — including multilingual outreach.</p>

<h3>CPAC and the Chamber</h3>
<p>The Cloverdale Performing Arts Center asked for an additional $25,000 in 26–27, and the Chamber of Commerce asked for an additional $21,539 on top of its existing $133,000 base contract. The City Clerk's office reported that an Amendment 4 to the CPAC agreement is currently in negotiations.</p>

<h2>Planning, Public Works, and Capital Projects</h2>

<p>Beyond the discretionary list, staff walked the Council through ongoing capital work. Notable lines on the Water Enterprise side include <strong>$470,000</strong> for water infrastructure tied to the Clark Avenue reconstruction, <strong>$584,826</strong> in 26–27 plus another <strong>$1 million</strong> in 27–28 for the South Crest Tank, and ongoing tank/reservoir rehab and pipe replacement at $500,000 and $185,000 per year, respectively. On the planning side, $20,000 for code enforcement and $90,000 for a West Hills Annexation consultant — a portion of which may be reimbursable through LAFCO — round out the asks.</p>

<h2>Public Comment: A Pointed Letter on Water Rates</h2>

<p>The workshop's public-comment portion included a written submission from resident Rob Koslowsky, sent the morning of the meeting, taking sharp aim at consultant West Yost's April 2026 letter on the aging Cherry Creek (Southcrest) reservoir. Koslowsky argued that the 60-year-old reservoir has been the subject of repeated studies dating back to the 2010 Water System Master Plan, that ratepayers have already absorbed substantial rate increases tied to capital improvements that include this site, and that further deferral amounts to "more studies" without the replacement getting built. He also proposed an immediate sewer rate reduction from $62.77 to $57.06 — back to 2024 levels — followed by inflation-only increases for one year rather than the multi-year escalator currently in place, partly on grounds of fairness to fixed-income residents and seniors.</p>

